                            <h1>
                            Your Own Personal Testimony
                            </h1>
                            <h2 class="author">
                                    <div class="byline" id="">
				<p uri="/ensign/2000/05/your-own-personal-testimony.p2" class="">Elder Angel Abrea</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/2000/05/your-own-personal-testimony.p" class="">Of the Seventy</p>
			</div>   
                                    </h2>
                            <hr>
                        </div><!-- end #details -->
                       
                        <div id="primary">
                            
                            
                            <blockquote class="intro dontHighlight">
                                        
                                        
                                        <div class="kicker" id="">The Holy Ghost has the power to bring light and understanding to our lives, but we must pay the price to seek and win His companionship.</div>
                                        
                                    </blockquote>
                            
                            <span style="display: none" id="article-id">20905_000_020</span>
			<div class="figure">
				<img src="/bc/content/shared/content/images/gospel-library/magazine/ensignlp.nfo:o:1763.jpg" alt="Elder Angel Abrea">
			</div>
			<p uri="/ensign/2000/05/your-own-personal-testimony.p4" class="">I would like to have an imaginary conversation about personal testimony with the priesthood holders. I believe that this colloquial way will help me to convey my message. For the purpose of our discussion, I will use the names of my grandsons; please imagine that these names are yours and that I am speaking directly to each one of you young men.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2000/05/your-own-personal-testimony.p5" class="">My dear James, when you were a young boy you bore your testimony and said, &ldquo;I know the gospel is true. I know that <a class="no-link-style" href="http://mormon.org/jesus-christ">Jesus Christ</a> is the Son of God. I know that <a class="no-link-style" href="http://mormon.org/joseph-smith/">Joseph Smith</a> was a true prophet.&rdquo; You knew those things because others told you. Because of your trust in your parents, your bishop, and others, you never questioned that knowledge. But now, as you grow more independent in understanding, comprehension, and perception of all the different variables that this intense and beautiful life presents to you, frequently you realize that not all men have the same testimony or the &ldquo;peace of God, which passeth all understanding&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/philip/4.7?lang=eng#6" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Philip. 4:7</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2000/05/your-own-personal-testimony.p6" class="">Maybe, Jonathan, you have already realized that some adults are cynical and will not talk to you about the beautiful concepts of the Atonement, the <a class="no-link-style" href="http://lds.org/ensign/2000/05/resurrection?lang=eng">Resurrection</a>, and eternal life. Instead, they will tell you to &ldquo;eat, drink, and be merry, for tomorrow we die&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/2-ne/28.7?lang=eng#6" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">2 Ne. 28:7</a>). Others you will see groping and grasping, looking for answers which they do not find. And yet they will still try to demonstrate to you a knowledge of that which they do not have. Even others will say, &ldquo;Well, maybe these things are true, but maybe they aren&rsquo;t. The best thing we can do is live our own lives the way we see fit, and then if there is a life after this one, we will see what happens.&rdquo;</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2000/05/your-own-personal-testimony.p7" class="">Now, Andrew, I can understand the thoughts and feelings you may have in your mind and heart. I can understand that when you listen to these different messages, you may ask yourself what is right and what is not.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2000/05/your-own-personal-testimony.p8" class="">I&rsquo;m sure that many questions have come to your mind. The truth is that you will not be condemned for wondering or questioning if you make a sincere effort to find the answer. Our mental powers have been given to us to use. Faith based on personal prayer, study, and obedience is more lasting than blind faith; it is more rewarding, and for sure it is better grounded.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2000/05/your-own-personal-testimony.p9" class="">And you, Paul, do you remember when the Savior said: &ldquo;Verily I say unto you, Except ye be converted, and become as little children, ye shall not enter into the kingdom of heaven. Whosoever therefore shall humble himself as this little child, the same is greatest in the kingdom of heaven&rdquo;? (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/matt/18.3-4?lang=eng#2" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Matt. 18:3&ndash;4</a>). We are benefited by retaining the humility and teachableness of a child, but we must be sure to continue growing and not be content with the limited knowledge or comprehension of the gospel which a child has. Remember, Paul, what the Apostle of your same name said to the Corinthians: &ldquo;Brethren, be not children in understanding: howbeit in malice be ye children, but in understanding be men&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/1-cor/14.20?lang=eng#19" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">1 Cor. 14:20</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2000/05/your-own-personal-testimony.p10" class="">Well now, my dear Russell, you will ask yourself, &ldquo;In that case, do I have to go and look for the answer myself? Can anybody have this kind of testimony? Is it a gift only for a few? Do those who say they <span class="emphasis">know</span> really only <span class="emphasis">think</span> they know, or have they convinced themselves through a psychological trick?&rdquo;</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2000/05/your-own-personal-testimony.p11" class="">In answer to your questions, and to give more light to these things, let me tell you that Elder John A. Widtsoe said that those who truly have a testimony of the gospel have &ldquo;the highest type of knowledge. It comes as a revelation when truth is known and obeyed. &hellip; It is really <span class="emphasis">man&rsquo;s chief possession</span>&rdquo; (&ldquo;What Does It Mean to Have a Testimony?&rdquo; <span class="emphasis">Improvement Era,</span> May 1945, 273; emphasis added). Do you realize that a testimony is defined as &ldquo;the highest type of knowledge&rdquo; and &ldquo;man&rsquo;s chief possession&rdquo; and that in the Doctrine and Covenants the Savior mentions it as a knowledge &ldquo;which shall dwell in your heart&rdquo;? (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/8.2?lang=eng#1" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 8:2</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2000/05/your-own-personal-testimony.p12" class="">Maybe it will be difficult to understand this at your age, but our testimony is something that we will take with us to the next life. We will leave all our earthly possessions behind, but that knowledge, that inner conviction, will remain with us. Think of Joseph Smith: those who took his life could not take his chief possession&mdash;his testimony. The Prophet Joseph took that priceless possession with him through death&rsquo;s veil into eternity, where the Lord had promised him &ldquo;a throne for you in the kingdom of my Father&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/132.49?lang=eng#48" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 132:49</a>). But at the same time, that testimony, together with &ldquo;a fame and name that cannot be slain&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/135.3?lang=eng#2" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 135:3</a>), remains here with us. We hear the resounding witness of God&rsquo;s Prophet testifying &ldquo;that [<a class="no-link-style" href="http://jesuschrist.lds.org/">Christ</a>] lives! For we saw him, even on the right hand of God; and we heard the voice bearing record that he is the Only Begotten of the Father&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/76.22-23?lang=eng#21" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 76:22&ndash;23</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2000/05/your-own-personal-testimony.p13" class="">My dear Matthew, now that you have been able to see the eternal dimension of a testimony, we can continue with our conversation, showing that you can have your own testimony if you do what is necessary to obtain one.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2000/05/your-own-personal-testimony.p14" class="">In one of those difficult times that the faithful and dedicated young Nephi had with his rebellious brothers, he reminded them of the following guide to obtaining a testimony. The Lord declared, &ldquo;If ye will not harden your hearts, and ask me in faith, believing that ye shall receive, with diligence in keeping my commandments, surely these things shall be made known unto you&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/1-ne/15.11?lang=eng#10" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">1 Ne. 15:11</a>). Now, we can review the steps Nephi described.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2000/05/your-own-personal-testimony.p15" class="">First, <span class="emphasis">don&rsquo;t harden your heart.</span> Seek to know. In other words, have an intense, consuming desire to know. Give place for a seed to be planted in your heart. And if you do this, do you know what the promise is? Alma tells us, &ldquo;He that will not harden his heart, to him is given &hellip; to know the mysteries of God&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/alma/12.10?lang=eng#9" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Alma 12:10</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2000/05/your-own-personal-testimony.p16" class="">Second, <span class="emphasis">ask in faith.</span> In your study of the scriptures, have you noted how many times the phrase &ldquo;believing that ye shall receive&rdquo; accompanies the commandment of praying and asking? In the process of asking for knowledge, we have to exercise faith&mdash;believing before receiving. To illustrate this part of our conversation, Alma gives us a good example when he explained how he obtained his testimony:</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2000/05/your-own-personal-testimony.p17" class="">&ldquo;Behold, I have fasted and prayed many days that I might know these things of myself. And now I do know of myself that they are true; for the Lord God hath made them manifest unto me by his Holy Spirit; and this is the spirit of revelation which is in me&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/alma/5.46?lang=eng#45" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Alma 5:46</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2000/05/your-own-personal-testimony.p18" class="">Third, <span class="emphasis">keep the commandments.</span> I think that the words of the Book of Mormon point out the blessings that we can obtain if we abound in good works. King Benjamin declared to his people, &ldquo;If you believe all these things see that ye do them&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/mosiah/4.10?lang=eng#9" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Mosiah 4:10</a>). And the great missionary Ammon said, &ldquo;Yea, he that repenteth and exerciseth faith, and bringeth forth good works, and prayeth continually without ceasing&mdash;unto such it is given to know the mysteries of God&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/alma/26.22?lang=eng#21" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Alma 26:22</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2000/05/your-own-personal-testimony.p19" class="">Now, Cole, we have analyzed the different steps we should follow in our search for a testimony. But there is yet the most important help available that can give us confirmation and absolute assurance, and it is your right when you live worthy to receive the companionship of the Holy Ghost. Remember the promise in Moroni: &ldquo;And by the power of the Holy Ghost ye may know the truth of all things&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/moro/10.5?lang=eng#4" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Moro. 10:5</a>). Pay attention that I said to <span class="emphasis">receive</span> the companionship of the Holy Ghost. The Holy Ghost has the power to bring light and understanding to our lives, but we must pay the price to seek and win His companionship.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2000/05/your-own-personal-testimony.p20" class="">Elder Marion G. Romney once wrote: &ldquo;It is the mission of the Holy Ghost to reveal the truth of heaven to those who qualify to receive it. Every one of us, if we will, may so qualify. We must ever keep in mind, however, that he will not dwell in an unholy environment. He is used to the society of God, for he is an associate of the Father and the Son. When we receive the gift of the Holy Ghost, we are commanded to receive him; he is not commanded to come to us. But if, with all our hearts, we truly seek him, he will come to us and guide us in the making of decisions at every crisis of our lives&rdquo; (&ldquo;Revelation in Our Personal Affairs,&rdquo; <span class="emphasis">Relief Society Magazine,</span> Oct. 1955, 647). The Holy Ghost is given to us to witness of the Father and the Son; that Jesus Christ is our Redeemer; that there is a prophet upon the earth who presides over the true Church that carries the Savior&rsquo;s name, even The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints; and that all the works and promises of God will be fulfilled in His time and in His own way.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2000/05/your-own-personal-testimony.p21" class="">And now, my youngest grandson, Tate, we can end this conversation, mentioning what a testimony is. Maybe the best way to define it would be by looking at what a testimony represents in our lives. It is to say, &ldquo;I will go and do the things which the Lord hath commanded, for I know&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/1-ne/3.7?lang=eng#6" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">1 Ne. 3:7</a>), and then to act in consequence. It is to have the peace that comes with knowing that all possible has been done, that all talents have been exercised to the maximum. It is to follow the commandment of the Lord to Joshua: &ldquo;Be strong and of a good courage; be not afraid, neither be thou dismayed: for the Lord thy God is with thee whithersoever thou goest&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/ot/josh/1.9?lang=eng#8" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Josh. 1:9</a>). And it is to &ldquo;be patient in afflictions&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/31.9?lang=eng#8" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 31:9</a>). It is to never give up, but to stand up as an example to others. It is to &ldquo;be ready always to give an answer to every man that asketh you a reason of the hope that is in you with meekness and fear&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/1-pet/3.15?lang=eng#14" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">1 Pet. 3:15</a>). It is to declare His generation: &ldquo;Jesus Christ [is] the Son of God, the Father of heaven and earth, the Creator of all things from the beginning&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/mosiah/3.8?lang=eng#7" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Mosiah 3:8</a>). Yes, these and many other characteristics and actions model a testimony. And this is my testimony to you in the name of Jesus Christ, amen.</p>
		
                            
                            
                            
